---
import Primer from '../../layouts/Primer.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';
---
<Primer
  title="Inside the Network"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter Three"
  deck="The last chapter left one box shut: how a neighborhood of atoms becomes a single number. This chapter opens it, and follows the field from hand-built features to networks that learn their own."
  running="Ch. 3 — Inside the Network"
  prev={{ href: url('/primer/atoms-as-a-graph'), label: 'Atoms as a Graph' }}
  next={{ href: url('/primer/how-one-gets-made'), label: 'How One Gets Made' }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    Chapter 2 built everything up to one door and stopped there. The energy is a sum of per-atom
    pieces, <em>E</em> = Σ<sub>i</sub> ε<sub>i</sub>; each piece ε<sub>i</sub> looks only at the
    atoms inside atom <em>i</em>'s cutoff, described by quantities that survive sliding, turning,
    and relabeling — distances, angles, and element. What Chapter 2 did not say is how that
    description becomes the number ε<sub>i</sub>. That is the function we open now.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 1</span>The first answer: describe the patch by hand</h2>

  <p>
    The earliest answer was direct: turn each atom's neighborhood into a fixed list of numbers, then
    feed that list to a small network. The list is the hard part, and it is where the physics goes
    in.
  </p>

  <p>
    A neighborhood is, at bottom, the distances to the neighbors and the angles between them. So
    build numbers out of exactly those. Take a <strong>radial feature</strong>: pick a target
    distance — say two ångströms (Å) — and, for each neighbor, score how close it sits to that
    target, full marks if it lands right on it and fading to nothing as it moves away. Add those
    scores over all the neighbors. The result is one number that answers a single plain question:
    how many neighbors sit about two ångströms out? Pick a different target distance and you get
    another number, another question. A row of such features, with targets spread across the cutoff,
    sketches the radial shell-by-shell profile of the patch.
  </p>

  <p>
    Distances alone cannot tell a flat arrangement from a bunched one, so add
    <strong>angular features</strong> built the same way: for every pair of neighbors, score the
    angle they make at the central atom against a target angle, and sum over all the pairs. Now the
    list also knows whether the neighbors fan out or crowd together.
  </p>

  <p>
    Each of these numbers is a sum over neighbors, so the order you list the neighbors in does not
    matter — there is the permutation symmetry of Chapter 2, built in for free. And because the
    ingredients are distances and angles, sliding or turning the molecule leaves every number alone.
    The whole list is invariant by construction. These hand-built numbers have a name:
    <strong>symmetry functions</strong>, or more loosely <strong>descriptors</strong> — a fixed
    vector that describes the patch.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hand that vector to a small neural network and let it return ε<sub>i</sub>. One network per
    element: carbon's neighborhoods are scored by carbon's network, oxygen's by oxygen's, so the
    same chemistry is read the same way wherever it appears. Sum the ε<sub>i</sub> over all atoms
    and you have the energy. This is the <strong>Behler–Parrinello</strong> scheme, set down in 2007
    by Jörg Behler and Michele Parrinello — the work that opened the field this primer is about.
  </p>

