  </figure>

  <p>
    The rounds buy something the cutoff alone cannot give: range. Think of it as gossip. After one
    round, your scratchpad holds news from the atoms you talk to directly — the ones inside your
    cutoff. But those atoms have been talking too. After a second round, the news they pass you
    already carries what <em>their</em> neighbors told them, so you have heard, secondhand, from
    atoms two edges away — atoms you never spoke to. After three rounds the gossip has reached you
    from three edges out. The number of rounds sets how far through the material an atom's energy can
    feel, the model's <strong>receptive field</strong>.
  </p>

  <aside class="sidenote">
    <span class="sn-label">Two ranges, not one</span>
    The cutoff and the receptive field are different knobs and it is easy to confuse them. The
    <em>cutoff</em> decides who you talk to in a single round — your direct neighbors, a few
    ångströms out. The <em>number of rounds</em> decides how many hops the gossip travels, and so
    how far the influence reaches in total. Three rounds with a five-ångström cutoff lets an atom
    feel structure roughly fifteen ångströms away, without ever drawing an edge that long.
  </aside>

