  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>What the messages carry</h2>

  <p>
    Message passing learns its own features, but it inherits a question from Chapter 2: how much of
    the geometry do the messages keep? The plainest version sends only scalars — numbers built from
    distances, like "this neighbor is 2.1 Å away." Scalars are invariant; they do not change when
    you turn the molecule, which is exactly what an energy needs. An early and influential model,
    <strong>SchNet</strong>, was built this way, on distances alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Distance-only messages have the same blind spot the hand-built descriptors had before angles
    were added. Look at a central atom with two neighbors, each the same distance out, and swing
    the angle between them from wide to narrow. Every message the center receives is unchanged —
    this neighbor at 2.1 Å, that neighbor at 2.1 Å — yet the arrangement has changed, and so has
    its energy. A model that hears only distances reads the two as identical.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 230" role="img" aria-label="Two neighborhoods of a central atom with two neighbors at identical distances but a different angle between them: one wide open, one folded narrow.">
        <text x="190" y="36" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">angle wide</text>
        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.6">
