        <circle cx="190" cy="162" r="8" fill="var(--oxblood)" />
        <text x="128" y="140" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₁</text>
        <text x="252" y="140" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₂</text>

        <text x="530" y="36" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">angle narrow</text>
        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.6">
          <line x1="530" y1="162" x2="492" y2="59" />
          <line x1="530" y1="162" x2="568" y2="59" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)"><circle cx="492" cy="59" r="7"/><circle cx="568" cy="59" r="7"/></g>
        <circle cx="530" cy="162" r="8" fill="var(--oxblood)" />
        <text x="496" y="120" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₁</text>
        <text x="564" y="120" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₂</text>

        <text x="360" y="206" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small" style="fill:var(--oxblood);">same d₁ and d₂ — different angle, different energy</text>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 4</span>Two neighborhoods the center atom cannot tell apart by distance alone: both neighbors sit at the same distances <em>d</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>d</em><sub>2</sub>, but the angle between them differs. Distance-only messages are identical in the two cases; the true energies are not.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    There are two ways to fix this. The first is to put the missing geometry back in by hand: feed
    angles to the messages, the way the hand-built descriptors did. Models in the
    <strong>DimeNet</strong> and <strong>GemNet</strong> line do this, sending messages that carry
    angle information as well as distance. The features are still scalars — still invariant — but now
    they encode shape, not just spacing.
  </p>

  <p>
    The second way is deeper. Let the scratchpads themselves hold directional things. Instead of
    attaching a plain number to each neighbor, attach a little arrow that points along the bond. An
    arrow records direction, not just spacing. Beyond the arrow come richer directional patterns —
    two lobes, four lobes, finer and finer — with the arrow as the coarsest member of the family.
    These building blocks are the <strong>spherical harmonics</strong>, the same objects physics
    uses to describe atomic orbitals and angular momentum.
    Their defining property is the one we need: when the molecule turns, they turn rigidly with it —
    they are <strong>equivariant</strong>, the same word Chapter 2 used for forces. Rotation now lives
    <em>inside</em> the network's hidden layers, not only at its input and output. Models in the
    <strong>NequIP</strong>, <strong>MACE</strong>, and <strong>Allegro</strong> family work this way.
  </p>

  <aside class="sidenote">
    <span class="sn-label">What equivariance buys</span>
    Not correctness — Chapter 2 showed that an invariant energy, differentiated, gives equivariant
    forces for free, and SchNet and DimeNet, whose insides are entirely invariant, get their forces
    exactly this way. The payoff is <em>efficiency</em>: a network that already speaks the language
    of rotation does not have to learn it from examples, and so learns the rest from far fewer of
    them. NequIP reported matching the accuracy of earlier invariant models with a small fraction of
    the training data they needed — on some benchmarks a thousandth as many examples.
  </aside>

  <p>
    Depth is not the only route to expressiveness. MACE packs more into each round instead of
    stacking rounds: its messages mix pairs and triples of neighbors at once — <strong>higher body
    order</strong>, in the field's vocabulary — so about two rounds do what plainer models need five
    or six for.
  </p>

  <p>
    Whatever the family, one thing holds across nearly all of them. The network is built
    to produce the energy, a single invariant number, and the forces are taken by differentiating
    that energy — <em>F</em> = −∇<em>E</em>, the rule from Chapter 1. The forces are never a second,
    separate output that might quietly disagree with the energy; they are its exact slope, which is
    what keeps a long simulation from leaking or inventing energy as it runs.
  </p>

  <p>
    The machine now has its shape: rounds of messages, features plain or directional, a readout
    that sums per-atom energies. A shape is not yet a model. Inside every shaping and updating step
    sit adjustable numbers — thousands to millions of them, the <strong>weights</strong> — and
    nothing so far has said how they get their values. They are set by example — and the examples
    have to come from somewhere.
  </p>

